hands_on_practices.solution:
We use homology relations for a radiative, ideal-gas star with Kramers opacity $\kappa\propto\rho T^{-3.5}$ and energy generation $\epsilon\propto\rho T^{\nu}$, mass $M$ constant.

1. Central scaling relations:
$$\rho_c\sim\frac{M}{R^3},\qquad 
P_c\sim\frac{G\,M^2}{R^4},\qquad
T_c\sim\frac{\mu\,P_c}{\rho_c}\sim\frac{\mu\,G\,M}{R}.$$

2. Nuclear luminosity:
$$L_{\rm nuc}\sim\epsilon_c\,M\propto\rho_c\,T_c^{\nu}\,M
\propto\frac{M}{R^3}\Bigl(\frac{\mu M}{R}\Bigr)^{\nu}M
\;\Rightarrow\;
L_{\rm nuc}\propto\mu^{\nu}M^{\nu+2}R^{-(\nu+3)}.$$

3. Radiative luminosity:
$$L_{\rm rad}\sim\frac{16\pi acG}{3}\frac{M\,T_c^4}{\kappa_cP_c}
\propto\frac{M\,T_c^4}{(\rho_cT_c^{-3.5})(\rho_cT_c/\mu)}
\propto M\,\mu\,\frac{T_c^{6.5}}{\rho_c^2}
\;\Rightarrow\;
L_{\rm rad}\propto\mu^{7.5}M^{5.5}R^{-0.5}.$$

4. Setting $L_{\rm nuc}=L_{\rm rad}$ gives
$$\mu^{\nu}M^{\nu+2}R^{-(\nu+3)}
\propto\mu^{15/2}M^{11/2}R^{-1/2}
\quad\Rightarrow\quad
R\propto\mu^{\frac{2\nu-15}{2\nu+5}}M^{\frac{2\nu-7}{2\nu+5}}.$$

5. Then
$$L\propto\mu^{\frac{14\nu+45}{2\nu+5}}M^{\frac{10\nu+31}{2\nu+5}},\qquad
T_{\rm eff}\propto L^{1/4}R^{-1/2}
\propto\mu^{\frac{10\nu+75}{4(2\nu+5)}}M^{\cdots}.$$

6. Along the evolutionary track $M$ constant, so 
$$\frac{d\log L}{d\log T_{\rm eff}}
=\frac{d\log L/d\log\mu}{d\log T_{\rm eff}/d\log\mu}
=\frac{\frac{14\nu+45}{2\nu+5}}{\frac{10\nu+75}{4(2\nu+5)}}
=\frac{4(14\nu+45)}{10\nu+75}=\frac{56\nu+180}{10\nu+75}.$$
